<p>
  Prep survey for decision
  <a href="/backlog/1816-conformance-model-for-non-facts-verdict-relocated-runtimes/">#1816</a> (parent
  <a href="/backlog/1294-relocate-we-resident-logic-reference-runtimes/">#1294</a>), the non-engine
  complement of the resolved facts→verdict KIT
  <a href="/backlog/1784-conformance-kit-for-the-facts-verdict-relocated-engines/">#1784</a>. The #1294
  relocation cascade proves conformance with the #899/#1789 <em>interaction-script</em> vector model — a
  binding is driven (<code>dispatch(step)</code>) and a typed surface read (<code>observe(surface)</code>),
  judged against <code>expect</code>. Four relocated <strong>non-engine</strong> runtimes produce output
  that is <strong>not a verdict</strong>: webtheme token-projection (DTCG → resolved map, #404), intl
  formatting (native <code>Intl.*</code> instances → locale strings), analytics aggregation, and
  reliability provider-strategy (a typed <code>RecoveryResult</code>). How do they prove conformance
  through the plateau-hosted runner?
</p>

<h2>The headline finding — the model is not verdict-locked, and a second shape already exists</h2>
<p>
  Two load-bearing facts in the real tree dissolve most of the apparent fork:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>The interaction-script <code>expect</code> is already open-ended.</strong>
    <code>ConformanceExpectation</code> is <code>{ finalState?, neverObserved?, aria?, [assertion]:
    unknown }</code> (<code>we:conformance-vectors/schema.ts:38-47</code>), and the judge compares every
    non-special key against the final snapshot via strict <code>===</code>
    (<code>plateau:src/conformance-engine/conformanceVectors.ts:142-147</code>). webcompliance already
    observes a <strong>number</strong> (<code>violationCount</code>) and booleans through this path
    (<code>we:conformance-vectors/webcompliance.vectors.ts</code>). "Observe a verdict" was always
    shorthand for "observe a typed surface."
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>A golden-output suite shape already ships</strong> — the Doc-Spec suite (#1163,
    <code>we:conformance-vectors/webdocs.vectors.ts</code>): <code>{ manifest, cases, expect: DocsSite
    }</code>, a pure-transform vector judged by <strong>deep-equality</strong>, exported as a deliberately
    separate shape (<code>we:conformance-vectors/index.ts:20-22</code>). So sketch-candidate (B) is not an
    invention — it is reusing a proven precedent. webtheme token-projection is the same kind of artifact.
  </li>
</ul>

