<p>
  The three sketched candidates collapse: (A) and (B) are <em>both</em> already real and complementary, so
  the answer is <strong>support-both, classified by output nature</strong>. The one genuine fork is the
  <strong>comparison semantics</strong> — strict <code>===</code> suffices for scalars but not for
  structured or locale-sensitive output. Resolve it with a small <strong>closed matcher set</strong> —
  <code>{ exact · deep-equal · resolved-options/parts-structure }</code> — carried as an
  <code>expect</code>/golden tag in the WE schema and interpreted by the Plateau judge. <strong>Reject (C)
  per-shape binding bases</strong> (formatter-judge / aggregator-judge / token-projector-judge): a matcher
  is a comparison tag, not a fresh driver, so (C) is judge proliferation for no merit gain.
</p>

<h2>Why intl forces the third matcher (the skeptic's refutation)</h2>
<p>
  A refute-only skeptic <strong>refuted exact-equality for intl</strong>: formatted output depends on the
  host engine's ICU/CLDR version (e.g. the U+202F narrow-no-break-space that replaced the ASCII space
  before AM/PM around ICU 72), so a golden or deep-equal <code>expect</code> produces false negatives that
  track the <em>engine</em>, not the implementation under test — the exact failure Test262's Intl suite is
  engineered to avoid. Because the corpus (WE) and the executing engine (Plateau runner / FUI binding) sit
  on different layers by design, equality of any flavor is the wrong oracle for intl. The fix —
  asserting <code>resolvedOptions()</code> and <code>formatToParts</code> part structure — is folded in as
  the third matcher. It <strong>sharpens</strong> the fork (the real call is comparison semantics, not
  model shape) without resurrecting (C): a matcher is a schema tag, not a binding base. Verdict:
  <strong>SURVIVES-WITH-AMENDMENT</strong>.
</p>

